Na5 ({The energetic} 13... g5 $6 {is a dubious idea, as is demonstrated in the
following lines:} 14. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 15. Bxg5 Kh7 (15... Kg7 16. Re3 $18 {
[%cal Ge3g3]}) 16. Qf3 Kg7 17. Qg3 Rh8 (17... Nh5 18. Bxe7+ Nxg3 19. Bxf8+ $18)
18. Re3 {[%cal Ge3f3]} Qe8 19. Rf3 Nh5 (19... Ng4 20. Bf6+ $1 $18) 20. Qh4 {
[%cal Gf3f7,Gb3f7] The f7-pawn is a converging point of attack. Black's king
is too exposed and fails to assemble an adequate defense.} Kg8 {[%cal Ge8f7]}
21. d4 $1 {With no hurry to capture the f7-pawn.} Rh7 22. Rxf7 Qxf7 23. Bxf7+
Kxf7 24. dxe5 Nxe5 25. f4 Ng4 26. h3 $16) 14. d4 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Rad8 16. h3 c5
17. Qd2 Rfe8 18. b4 $14) 12. Bb3 Qe7 13. Re1 Na5 14. d4 Rbd8 15. h3 Kh7 (15...
g5 $2 {As we have already seen in this chapter, this is a bad idea again.} 16.
Nxg5 $1 hxg5 17. Bxg5 Kh7 (17... Nxb3 18. Rxb3 $1 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gb3g3] Now,
White's queenside rook will swing to the kingside via the 3rd rank after c3-c4.
} Kh7 (18... Kg7 19. c4 $18 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gb3f3,Gg5f6,Gf3f6]}) 19. Qf3 (19.
c4 $2 {This gives Black a chance to defend, allowing him to include the rooks
in the game.} Rg8 $1 $15) 19... Kg7 20. Qg3 Rg8 21. Rxb7 Rc8 22. Re3 $18) (
17... Kg7 18. Re3 $18 {[%cal Ge3f3]}) 18. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gd1f3,Gg5f6]
