Bxf6+ Kxf6 21.Qh4+ Ke6 22.d5++.} Rg8 {White has two paths towards victory:} (
19... Nxb3 20. Bxf6+ Kxf6 21. Qh4+ Kg6 (21... Ke6 22. d5#) 22. Qxe7 $18) (19...
Rh8 {[%cal Rg3h4]} 20. Bxf6+ Kxf6 21. f4 $1 exf4 22. Rf1 $18) 20. Bxf6+ $1 (20.
f4 $1 Kf8 (20... Nh5 21. Bf6+ $3 {A very pretty bishop check!} Kh7 22. Qxg8+
$18) 21. Qh4 Rxg5 22. fxg5 Ng8 23. Bxf7 $18 {[%cal Ge1f1]}) 20... Kxf6 21. Qh4+
Rg5 22. f4 $1 exf4 23. Qh6+ Rg6 24. e5+ dxe5 (24... Kf5 $2 {This leads to a
forced checkmate.} 25. Qh5+ $1 Rg5 (25... Qg5 26. g4+ fxg3 27. Rf1+ Ke4 28.
Qf3# {#}) 26. g4+ fxg3 27. Rf1+ Ke4 28. Qf3# {#}) 25. Qh4+ Rg5 26. Rxe5 $18 {
And White won quickly in 1-0 (28) Rublevsky,S (2684)-Blagojevic,D (2516)
Valjevo 2011}) 16. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gc1g5] [#] A strong positional move.
White prevents g7-g5 and wants to play Qa3, looking for weaknesses to play on.}
Nxb3 17. axb3 Bc6 (17... Bc8 18. Qe3 (18. c4 $5 $14) 18... b6 19. c4 $14 {
1/2-1/2 (119) Chandler,M (2605)-Karpov,A (2730) Reykjavik 1991}) 18. Ra1 $1 {
[%csl Ga5,Re5][%cal Gd4e5,Gd6e5,Ga1a5] The e5-pawn is an unusual weakness that
Black has, and White's a1-rook can go to a5 in order to attack it.} Rg8 {
[%cal Gg7g5]} (18... exd4 $2 19. cxd4 Rde8 20. d5 Bd7 21. c4 Qd8 (21... g5 22.
Nxg5+ hxg5 23. Qxg5 $18) 22. Qc2 $16 {With a magnificent pawn center and a
very strong dark-squared bishop, White's position is very pleasant.}) 19. dxe5
$1 dxe5 20. Ra5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga5e5]} Bb5 21. c4 b6 22. Ra1 Bc6 23. Bxf6 $1
({The model game continues with} 23. Rxa6 g5 $1 24. Bg3 Nh5 (24... Nxe4 $1 {
This is the best move for Black.} 25. Nxe5 Nxg3 26. fxg3 Rge8 $13) 25. Nxe5 Bb7
26. Ra7 $14 {1-0 (31) Short,N (2635)-Speelman,J (2610)/London 1991/Candidates})
23... gxf6 (23... Qxf6 24. Rxa6 $16) 24. Nh4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh4f5]} Bd7 25.
Qe3 {It's necessary to defend the h3-pawn.} a5 26. Qf3 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1] White
enjoys a pleasant slight advantage without any risks. Conclusion: The modern
line with 8...h6 is very solid and perfectly playable for Black. As it was
discussed repeatedly, the g7-g5 advance can be severely punished, while in the
main line of 11...b5, White has a slight advantage, although sometimes the
position can be very close to equality.} *

