16. Nc4 b6 17. g3 Bd7 18. Bg2 h6 19. Ne3 $1 {As already mentioned, this is the
best square for the knight. Due to the closed character of the position, White
isn't in any rush and can slowly improve his pieces.} (19. f4 $2 {Is too
premature.} exf4 20. gxf4 ({The lesser evil is:} 20. Bxf4 $13 {and there is no
sign of an advantage for White.}) 20... Rae8 21. Qd3 Nh4 $1 22. Bh1 Bf5 $1 $17
{This is a strong counterplay by Black, demonstrating the dangers of rushing
with the f2-f4 break.}) 19... Nh7 20. c4 Rae8 {White has two promising
continuations that lead to an advantage.} 21. Qh5 {[%cal Rf7f5]} (21. a5 $16 {
White makes use of the space advantage and plays on both flanks.}) 21... Nf6
22. Qf3 {[%cal Ge3f5]} Bc8 23. Nf5 Bxf5 24. Qxf5 $16 {[%cal Ga4a5] White has a
space advantage and despite the center being closed, White's minor pieces are
superior since the knights don't have any outposts. Conclusion: In this old
variation which was once the main line, White has good prospects of gaining an
advantage. The plan to close the center with d4-d5 gives White a very
comfortable game with great chances to slowly outplay the opponent
positionally. In the line 9...h6 10.Bh4 Nd8, Black has good chances to create
some difficulties for White and it doesn't offer much of a peaceful play,
although Black's best option is probably Karpov's idea with 9...a6, where
Black achieves very solid positions that are difficult to crack.} *

