15. d5 Nd8 16. f4 {Usually, White must execute the f2-f4 break with greater
preparation and caution, but the passive placement of Black's pieces allows an
acceleration of the pawn avalanche on the kingside.} f6 17. c4 Nf7 18. f5 $1 {
White finished closing the center and will now concentrate on carrying out a
pawn avalanche on the kingside. This is especially good since Black is lacking
counterplay.} Re8 19. a4 $1 {As seen in the previous example, White is not in
a rush to provoke a quick confrontation on the kingside. Instead, White
prefers to pay attention and avoid any type of counterplay on the queenside by
his opponent.} Nf8 20. a5 Bd7 21. Bd2 Re7 22. Ra3 $1 {A useful multipurpose
move. The rook can swing across the third rank to the kingside or double on
the "a" or "b" files.} Nh8 23. Ng2 $1 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gh2h4,Ga3g3]} (23. g4 {
This isn't entirely accurate because Black can defend with:} g5 {Blocking the
kingside and hindering the advance of White's pawn avalanche.}) 23... g5 {
Black has to react somehow against the upcoming pawn storm from White, so this
blocking attempt is understandable.} (23... Rb8 24. h4 $1 {Avoiding Black's
defensive g7-g5 blocking idea.} (24. g4 {Also seems to be a very reasonable
