14. d5 Nf8 15. c4 $2 {This is a premature advance. It was much better to use
the c4-square by placing the knight there with the maneuver Nf3-Nd2-Nc4. Later
on, White can play on the queenside with the knight on c4 or continue with
Nc4-Ne3 and after that, c3-c4, and then play on the kingside.} (15. Nd2 $1)
15... Ng6 {Black prepares against the f2-f4 break. As seen in previous
examples, Black's position is passive and Black is forced to wait for White to
open up the position in order to get some counterplay.} 16. h3 h6 17. Nh2 Re8
18. Qd3 Nh7 $2 {Is too passive, this allows f2-f4 to be played in good
conditions for White.} ({It was best to continue developing with:} 18... Bd7 {
Now} 19. f4 $6 {is a bit hasty because White's pieces are lacking proper
coordination between each other.} ({A preferable move for White is:} 19. a4 $5
{and White can make progress step by step while avoiding Black's counterplay.})
19... exf4 20. gxf4 b5 $1 21. cxb5 c4 22. Qd4 Qb6 $1 $15 {With good
counterplay for Black.}) 19. f4 {This thematic pawn break is the main part of
the White's plan. Although it's acceptable in this position, it was
considerably stronger to prepare it first.} ({More suitable was} 19. Bg2 $16 {
[%cal Gh2f1,Gf1e3] followed by Nf1-Ne3/Bd2 and only then to consider f2-f4.})
19... exf4 20. gxf4 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Re1,Rf4][%cal Ge7h4,Gh4e1,Gg6f4] Black's
queen threatens to move to the kingside where it can cause problems. The other
moves are passive and docile.} (20... Nf6 21. Bd2 Bd7 (21... Nh5 22. Qf3 $18)
22. Qf3 $1 {Defending the f4-pawn in order to free the dark-squared bishop to
move.} b6 (22... b5 $5 23. Bc3 $1 bxc4 24. Re3 $1 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1]}) 23. Bc3
Qd8 24. Bd3 $18 {And White is ready to break the center with e4-e5.}) ({
The model game continued with:} 20... f5 $6 21. Qg3 $1 Nhf8 (21... Ngf8 $2 22.
e5 $18) 22. e5 $1 $16 dxe5 23. fxe5 f4 (23... Nxe5 $2 24. Bf4 Nfd7 25. Kh1 $1
$18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh2f3]}) 24. Qc3 b5 (24... Rxe5 $2 25. Bxf4 $18) 25. cxb5
Bb7 26. Bc4 Qd8 27. Nf3 {With a great advantage for White in ½-½ Watson,W  
(2535)-Mainka,R (2455)/Prague 1992}) 21. f5 $8 {The other options don't work
so well for White:} (21. Qf3 $2 Nf6 22. Bd3 b5 $1 {This is an excellent moment
for this pawn break!} 23. cxb5 c4 24. Bxc4 Nxe4 $17 {White's pawn structure is
very weak and the king is exposed.}) (21. Qg3 $2 Nf6 $1 22. f5 (22. Bd3 $4 Nh5
$1 23. Qf3 Qh4 $1 $19 {[%csl Re1,Rf4,Rh3][%cal Gh5f4,Gh4e1,Gc8h3]}) (22. e5 Nh5
23. Qf3 Qh4 $17 {Black's pieces are very active.}) 22... Nxe4 23. Rxe4 Qxe4 24.
fxg6 fxg6 $15 {With an unclear position, but it's easier to play with the
Black pieces.}) (21. Bg2 $2 Qf6 $1 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rf4][%cal Gg6f4,Gf6a1]})
21... Ne5 ({A serious mistake is:} 21... Bxf5 $2 22. exf5 Qxe1 23. fxg6 fxg6
24. Bb2 Qe3+ 25. Qxe3 Rxe3 26. Bc1 Re7 27. Bf4 $16 {After this forced sequence,
White has a clear advantage in the endgame.}) 22. Qg3 Kh8 23. Ng4 Ng5 (23...
Nf6 $2 24. Nxe5 Qxe5 $1 (24... dxe5 $2 25. Re2 Bd7 26. Rg2 Rg8 {White's
position is superior due to the passivity of Black's pieces. A possible plan
among many, is Bd3-Bd2-Kh2-Rag1, putting pressure on the g7-pawn.}) 25. Qxe5
Rxe5 26. Bb2 (26. Bd3 $6 Bxf5 $1 {Now this tactical blow works for Black.} 27.
Bb2 Bxh3 28. Bxe5 dxe5 29. Reb1 Rb8 30. Rb5 b6 31. Rab1 Nd7 $13 {With an
endgame that is difficult to evaluate.}) 26... Re7 $1 ({The e4-pawn is
poisoned.} 26... Rxe4 $2 27. Bxf6 Rxe1 28. Rxe1 gxf6 29. Re8+ Kg7 30. Rd8 $18)
27. Bd3 Nd7 28. Kf2 {And White can calmly seek to break the opponent's
position without taking major risks.}) (23... Nxg4 24. hxg4 f6 25. Bf4 Rd8 26.
Bd3 b6 27. Kg2 Bb7 28. Rh1 $16 {[%cal Gh1h2,Ga1h1,Gf4h6] White is going to
concentrate his forces on the sacrifice on the h6-pawn or proceed with the
