16... Nf4 {This position is from a game where 7.Ne2 has been played in the
Symmetrical Line. The resulting position is a hybrid between a Ruy Lopez
middlegame and an Italian Game. One of the characteristics that differentiate
it from other positions in the same line is the fact that Black didn't play
Bxc3 and White's pawn structure is intact.} 17. Nd2 $1 $16 {[%csl Gc4][%cal
Gd2c4] The knight moves to the c4-square where it can exert considerable
pressure on the queenside. To complement it, White plans to continue with
Nc4-Be3 and execute the b2-b4 pawn break at the right moment. It's worth
noting that the "active" Black knight on f4 isn't doing any damage.} g6 18. Nc4
Bd8 19. a5 $1 {White not only gains space on the queenside but also already
considers exchanging the light-squared bishops.} ({Another possible way to
make progress is:} 19. b4 cxb4 20. cxb4 Bd7 21. Be3 $16) 19... Bd7 20. Qf3 N4h5
21. Ba4 $1 {White is very happy to exchange the Black's best piece.} Nxg3 22.
Bxd7 Nxd7 23. Qxg3 Bf6 24. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4d7,Gg4e2]} Rad8 (24... Qe7 $2 25. Bxh6
$18) (24... Red8 25. a6 $1 {Creating weaknesses for Black on the queenside.} ({
Improving the pieces before playing a5-a6 is perfectly playable.} 25. Be3 Rac8
26. Rec1 Kg7 27. b4 $16) 25... b6 (25... b5 {Doesn't work well for Black.} 26.
Na5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ga5c6]} Nb6 27. Nc6 Rd7 28. Ra5 $18 {[%csl Rb5]}) 26. b4
cxb4 (26... Rac8 27. Na3 $18 {[%cal Ga3b5]}) 27. cxb4 Rac8 28. Na3 $18 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rd6][%cal Ga3b5,Gb5a7,Gb5d6] And Black's position collapses.})
25. b4 $1 $18 (25. a6 $5 {This idea that has been previously discussed is also
possible.} b6 26. Na3 Bg7 (26... h5 27. Qf3 Bg7 28. Nb5 $18) 27. Nb5 Nf6 28.
Qh4 g5 (28... Rd7 29. Bxh6 $18) 29. Qg3 Qe7 30. h4 $1 $18 {Black's light
squares are too weak.}) 25... h5 26. Qe2 cxb4 (26... Rc8 27. a6 $1 b6 28. Na3
$1 $18 {Again, an idea that was previously seen.}) 27. cxb4 a6 28. Be3 $1 {
White's bishop is placed on its best square and from here, it can contribute
on both sides of the board. There's too big of a difference in activity
between the minor pieces.} Rc8 29. Rac1 Qe7 30. Rc2 Rc7 31. Rec1 Rec8 32. Qd2
$18 {White has an absolutely dominant position. White should look for a timely
Nc4-b6, invading on the c-file. ½-½ (72) Campora,D (2549)-Atalik,S (2541)
