{White has sacrificed a knight with the idea to exploit Black's weak king
position. We are in a critical and very complex position. What is the most
accurate way for White to continue the initiative on the kingside?} 11. Nd5 $3
Bxd5 12. exd5 {With the obligatory exchange of pieces, White has achieved two
things: Black's valuable light-squared bishop has disappeared from the board,
and the e4-square has become available as a transfer square for White's pieces.
Here are some illustrative variations of the effectiveness of this sacrifice:}
Nb4 ({Another possibility for Black is:} 12... Nd4 13. c3 $3 Nxb5 14. Qf3 {
[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg5f6]} e4 $5 {With the pawn sacrifice, Black doesn't allow
White any ideas of using the e4-square anymore.} (14... Kg7 15. Rae1 $1 {
[%cal Ge1e4] White is down two pieces but is not interested in recovering some
material with 15.a4, but instead, White wants to transfer the rook to the
kingside via the e4-square.} Rh8 (15... c6 16. Re4 Nxe4 (16... Rh8 17. Bxf6+
Qxf6 18. Rg4+ Qg6 19. dxc6 bxc6 20. Rxg6+ Kxg6 21. a4 $18 {[%csl Rb5,Rc5][%cal
Gb2b4,Ga4a5] and one of the two Black's minor pieces will fall.}) 17. Bxd8
Raxd8 18. dxe4 $18 {[%csl Rb5,Rc5,Rg7] The weakness of Black's King in
addition to the poor coordination of Black's minor pieces, make Black's
position lost.}) 16. Re4 Nxe4 17. Bxd8 Raxd8 18. dxe4 a5 19. Qf5 $18 {With a
position very similar to the line with 15...c6.}) 15. dxe4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal
Ga2a4]} Kg7 {Isn't very useful either.} ({Returning the piece fails to defend
Black's position.} 15... Nd4 16. cxd4 Bxd4 {[%cal Gd4f6] Black's idea is that
now the bishop also contributes to the defense of the kingside.} 17. Rad1 Be5 (
17... Bxb2 $2 18. Qe2 $18 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gf2f4]}) 18. Qe2 Qd7 19. f4 $18) 16.
Rad1 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gd3g3]} Qe7 17. Rd3 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gd3g3]} Qe5 18. Bxf6+ Qxf6
19. Qg4+ Qg6 20. Qf4 $18 {[%cal Gd3g3]}) 13. d4 $1 {[#]} exd4 (13... Bxd4 14.
c3 $16) 14. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e4,Ge4g4,Ge4f4] This is the key idea, the rook
quickly joins the attack via the e4-square and then goes to f4 or the
g4-square.} Nbxd5 (14... Kg7 15. Re4 {[%cal Ge4f4,Ge4g4] Black doesn't have a
satisfactory solution.} Nbxd5 (15... a6 16. Bd3 Rh8 17. Qf3 Nbxd5 18. Rg4 Kf8
19. Bc4 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6]}) 16. Qf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge4g4,Gf3d5]} Rh8 17.
Rg4 Nxg4 18. Bxd8 Ne5 19. Qxd5 $18) 15. Qf3 Kg7 (15... c6 16. Re4 $1 Kg7 (16...
cxb5 17. Rh4 $18 {[%cal Gf3g3]}) 17. Bc4 Re8 18. Rg4 Nxg4 19. Bxd8 Ne5 20. Qg3+
$18) 16. Re4 $1 {Always the same rook maneuver.} Rh8 17. Rg4 Nxg4 18. Bxd8 Ne5
19. Qxd5 $18 *

